<subSubSection id="D9BC651EFFC6FFC7D495E043565B1A56" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="91193695FFC6FFC7D495E043565B1A56" blockId="26.[151,1437,151,1904]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D495E043560C1A2B" bold="true" box="[199,334,1556,1581]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Etymology.</emphasis>
Combination of Latin words 
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D6C8E043559C1A2B" box="[666,734,1556,1581]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">brevis</emphasis>
(small) and 
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D738E04254981A2A" box="[874,986,1557,1580]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">capitatum</emphasis>
(head), in reference to the short head of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D9BC651EFFC6FFC7D495E00B53C11B76" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="91193695FFC6FFC7D495E00B53C11B76" blockId="26.[151,1437,151,1904]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D495E00B560D1A73" bold="true" box="[199,335,1628,1653]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC6FFC7D504E00B55DE1A73" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[342,668,1628,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicapitatum">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D504E00B55DE1A73" box="[342,668,1628,1653]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Holopothrips brevicapitatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique within the genus for males having pore plates on sternites IV–VIII (
<figureCitation id="099D2A10FFC6FFC7D555E02856221A9E" box="[263,352,1663,1688]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–44" captionStartId="25.[151,264,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,327,1867]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[151,1436,327,1867]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURES 39–44. Holopothrips brevicapitatum sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (39) body; (40) head and pronotum; (41) metanotal sculpture; (42) pore plates on abdominal sternites IV–VIII (black arrows); (43) spermatheca; (44) pelta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445196/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
), while most 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC6FFC7D657E02855D81A9E" box="[517,666,1663,1688]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D657E02855D81A9E" box="[517,666,1663,1688]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Holopothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species have pore plates restricted to sternites VI–VIII. Only 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC6FFC7D1D3E0D657B61ABA" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="signatus">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D1D3E0D657B61ABA" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">H. signatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC6FFC7D551E0F256D41ABB" authority="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri, 2018" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[259,406,1700,1725]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singularis" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D551E0F256D41ABB" box="[259,406,1700,1725]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">H. singularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B8E157FCFFC6FFC7D5CCE0F3569C1ABB" box="[414,478,1700,1725]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" rank="species">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D5CCE0F3569C1ABB" bold="true" box="[414,478,1700,1725]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC6FFC7D5BEE0F2553A1ABB" authority="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri, 2018" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[492,632,1700,1725]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varicolor" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D5BEE0F2553A1ABB" box="[492,632,1700,1725]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">H. varicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B8E157FCFFC6FFC7D6D2E0F355821ABB" box="[640,704,1700,1725]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" rank="species">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D6D2E0F355821ABB" bold="true" box="[640,704,1700,1725]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
and specimens of possibly 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC6FFC7D7AAE0F2531D1ABA" box="[1016,1119,1701,1724]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pictus">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D7AAE0F2531D1ABA" box="[1016,1119,1701,1724]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">H. pictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have pore plates on sternite V, but never on IV. Another noteworthy trait of this species is the fore tarsal hamus being thin but apparently elongate, appearing to extend beyond the lateral margin of fore tarsus in some specimens. 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC6FFC7D154E0BB567D1B2E" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicapitatum">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D154E0BB567D1B2E" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Holopothrips brevicapitatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have some similarities with 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC6FFC7D6D4E14655AD1B2E" authorityName="Bagnall" authorityYear="1924" box="[646,751,1808,1832]" class="Insecta" family="Thysanoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phrasterothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D6D4E14655AD1B2E" box="[646,751,1808,1832]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">H. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC6FFC7D77AE146549B1B2E" box="[808,985,1809,1832]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="omercooperi">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D77AE146549B1B2E" box="[808,985,1809,1832]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">H. omercooperi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
such as the V-shaped stylets and striate metanotum, but is quickly distinguished by the shorter head and male pore plates. 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC6FFC7D006E16352DE1B4B" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[1108,1436,1844,1869]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicapitatum">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D006E16352DE1B4B" box="[1108,1436,1844,1869]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Holopothrips brevicapitatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found inducing rolled galls in 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC6FFC7D64EE10E553B1B76" box="[540,633,1881,1904]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Magnoliopsida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC6FFC7D64EE10E553B1B76" box="[540,633,1881,1904]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Miconia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
young leaves (
<figureCitation id="099D2A10FFC6FFC7D770E10054311B76" box="[802,883,1879,1904]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1359,1382]" captionTargetBox="[331,1256,294,1338]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[331,1256,293,1338]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–15. Leaf-galls induced by Holopothrips (white arrows). (10) galls on Myrtaceae (by H. flavisetis); (11) galls on Acca sellowiana (by H. infestans); 12–13. galls on Ƒochysia cf. obovata (by H. kaminskii) (Photos: Lucas A. Kaminski): (12) general view; (13) opened gall; (14) galls on Miconia sp. (by H. brevicapitatum); (15) galls on Tabebuia heterophylla (by H. tabebuia) (Photo: Irma Cabrera)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445186/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) in Southeastern 
<collectingCountry id="E9B17605FFC6FFC7D065E100533D1B76" box="[1079,1151,1879,1904]" name="Brazil" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
